+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Georgia Tech Unveils Prototype Nanogenerator                       |
|   from the power-to-go dept.                                       |
|   posted by CowboyNeal on Wednesday April 11, @13:47 (Power)       |
|   http://hardware.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/11/1721212     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Researchers at Georgia Institute of Technology have created a working
[0]prototype nanogenerator capable of generating as much as 4 watts per
cubic centimeter of continuous direct current. The generators are green
(to use), drawing power from natural motion in the surrounding
environment. They are based on non-toxic chemicals and should be safe for
use in biomechanical implants, but that's not their only potential use.
>From the article: "If you had a device like this in your shoes when you
walked, you would be able to generate your own small current to power
small electronics," Wang noted. "Anything that makes the nanowires move
within the generator can be used for generating power. Very little force
is required to move them."

Discuss this story at:
    http://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/11/1721212

Links:
    0. http://www.gatech.edu/news-room/release.php?id=1326


